Credit Card Fraud Prediction¶

Author : Nagarjuna Tella¶

A lot of companies handle huge amounts of transactions, they are able differentiate between fraudlent and non fradulent transactions. These companies handle this challenge by implementing Fraud Detection System (FDS). The best way to get a sense of the challenges underlying the design of a credit card fraud detection system (FDS) is by designing one.

Variance Inflation Factor¶

After the unessesary features have been eliminated, we'll check the Variance Inflation factor of the features to remove any features with factor greater than 4. With each iteration top 5 features are removed and VIF is computed to decrecrease Multicollinearity.

Summary of EDA¶

1) Data is clean.\ 2) No Null Values.\ 3) Important features are retained and remaining are dropped.\ 4) Most of the features are well distributed around the mean.\ 5) Dataset is highly Imbalanced.

Handling Imbalanced Data¶

Since the dataset is highly imbalanced with only 0.17% of fraudulent transactions, direct oversampling or undersampling will be inefficient. A mix of under and oversampling will help us cover more records.

1) Unsampling, non-fraudulent data by selecting random 10% of the tranasactions.\ 2) Oversampling it with fraudulent data to from the balanced dataset.

This can be handled in three ways. 1) Random Over Sampler(ROS)\ 2) Synthetic Data Vault(SDV)\ 3) Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique (SMOTE)

Classifier run pre-prosessing¶

In [33]:
# Function for Classifier Result
def cl_run(m, te, pr, pr_prob, x):
    print('======================================================')
    print(m)
    print('------------------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    precision = met.precision_score(te, pr)
    recall = met.recall_score(te, pr)
    accuracy = met.accuracy_score(te, pr)
    f1 = met.f1_score(te, pr)
    print('Accuracy of the model is', round(accuracy, 2))
    cl_rep = met.classification_report(te, pr)
    print(cl_rep)
    # Save the results in the DataFrame
    if x == 1:
        Result_sdv.loc[len(Result_sdv.index)] = [m, round(accuracy, 2), 
                                             round(precision, 2), round(recall, 2), round(f1, 2)]
    elif x == 2:
        Result_smote.loc[len(Result_smote.index)] = [m, round(accuracy, 2), 
                                                   round(precision, 2), round(recall, 2), round(f1, 2)]
    else:
        Result.loc[len(Result.index)] = [m, round(accuracy, 2), 
                                         round(precision, 2), round(recall, 2), round(f1, 2)]

    # Plotting Confusion Matrix
    cf_mtx = met.confusion_matrix(te, pr)
    ax = sns.heatmap(cf_mtx, annot=True, cmap='Blues', fmt='g')

    ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix for %s' % m)
    ax.set_xlabel('Predicted Values')
    ax.set_ylabel('Actual Values ')

    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['False', 'True'])
    ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['False', 'True'])

    plt.show()
    
    # Plotting ROC Curve
    plt.title(f'ROC Curve - %s' % m)
    fpr, tpr, thr = met.roc_curve(te, pr_prob)
    plt.plot(fpr,tpr,label="Area under the Curve="+str(round(accuracy, 2)))
    plt.legend(loc=4)
    plt.show()

Random Over Sampler¶

In [35]:
# Mix of Over and Under Sampling.
data_0 = data[data.Class == 0]
data_1 = data[data.Class == 1]

# We'll take random 10% of Non-Fraudulent data
sample_size = round(data_0.shape[0] * 0.1)

data_0_smp = resample(data_0, n_samples=sample_size, random_state=0)
data_smp = pd.concat([data_0_smp, data_1], axis=0)

x_smp = data_smp.drop('Class', axis=1)
y_smp = data_smp.Class

rs = RandomOverSampler(random_state=1)
X, Y = rs.fit_resample(x_smp, y_smp)
print(Y.value_counts())

scl = StandardScaler()
scl.fit(X)
X = scl.transform(X)

x_tr, x_te, y_tr, y_te = train_test_split(X, Y, stratify=Y, random_state=2)
print(y_tr.value_counts())
print(y_te.value_counts())

Summary¶

From the above results for all three sampling methods, entropy and information gain basically have same performance, so need to distinctly point that our. Entropy uses p*log(p) in error function vs information gain uses p^2 so only difference is mostly computational effort with optimizing since derivative of log is more complicated, but overall same accuracy can be expected.

Challenges faced :-

1) Overfitting

Decision tree has an AUC of 100%. This is clear overfitting (bias-variance tradeoff). Even GB tress are supposed to have pruning to stop overfitting, to mitigate that SMOTE was used and the results are better over SDV and ROS to mitigate Overfitting to a certain extent.

2) Hyperparameter tuning

For trees this might be necessary as a near 100% fit is clearly overfitting. with gridesearchCV over Tree, information gain and pruning parameters, we can see sublte difference in the results in terms of TP, FP, TN, FN.
